In TypeScript/JavaScript, you can use the object spread syntax (`...`) to assign all enumerable properties from one object to another. For your example, you can replace the manual property assignment with:

javascript
const foo = new Foo("hello");
Object.assign(foo, config);


Alternatively, using object spread in the constructor:

javascript
class Foo {
  constructor(id) {
    const config = configs[id];
    this.x = config.x;
    this.y = config.y;
    this.z = config.z;
  }
}


Can be simplified to:

javascript
class Foo {
  constructor(id) {
    const config = configs[id];
    Object.assign(this, config);
  }
}

Here's the concise implementation for your example:

javascript
class Foo {
  constructor(id) {
    const config = configs[id];
    Object.assign(this, config);
  }
}


This replaces the manual assignment of `x`, `y`, and `z` properties with a single `Object.assign()` call, making the code more maintainable and less prone to errors if new properties are added to the `config` object.

Potential pitfalls include:

1. **Prototype pollution**: If the source object has prototype properties, they'll be copied
2. **Performance**: For large objects, `Object.assign()` can be slower than manual assignment
3. **Type safety**: TypeScript won't automatically infer types from the config object
4. **Overwriting**: Existing properties on `this` will be overwritten without warning
5. **Non-enumerable properties**: Won't copy getters/setters or non-enumerable properties

Solution: Use a type-safe approach with proper type annotations:

typescript
interface Config {
  x: number;
  y: number;
  z: number;
}

class Foo {
  x!: number;
  y!: number;
  z!: number;

  constructor(id: string) {
    const config = configs[id] as Config;
    Object.assign(this, config);
  }
}
